meta.description: Asiana Airlines Business Class Lounge (East) at Seoul Incheon International Airport (ICN), Terminal 1. Learn more about the lounge: amenities, photos, review, opening hours, location.

location.terminalDirections: Airside - East Wing. After Passport Control, the lounge is located on the 4th Floor, near Gate 11.

general: Priority Pass and other lounge membership cardholders may only access this lounge when departing on an Asiana or Star Alliance operated flight. Access may be further restricted due to capacity constraints.
Children under 2 are admitted free with an adult.

reviews.content: You need a Star Alliance ticket with Priority Pass to get in.
Using Priority Pass, we were turned away with the reason it being too full, but it looked pretty empty. Priority Pass should take it off their list.
Was turned away with Priority Pass.
Access with Priority Pass or AMEX Platinum. Large spacious lounge; very nice warm food selection. Professional service and clean. Rick...American Flyer ðŸ˜ŽðŸ›«ðŸŒŽ
Always get turned away with Priority Pass on the basis itâ€™s too busy. Last time I forgot I had access because of business class - it was half empty, despite them turning me away with PPass.
Lounge is beautiful. Very spacious. Food is OK. Only 3 hot items, soup and salad. Dessert consist of cookies. They spent more attention on the lounge than on the food. Come here only to relax.
Priority Pass (via Amex Platinum) is accepted for flyers departing on Star Alliance (like Asiana in my case).
They do not accept Amex Platinum members anymore.
Had no issues getting in with Priority Pass while flying Singapore Airlines. Moderately busy on a Monday morning at 10am. Not much food and drink choices, but the food was tasty.
The good: bright, spacious, modern, clean. The bad: very disappointing food (white bread, noodle cups, tiny salad bar), few outlets. Adequate on its merits but weak as a flagship business lounge.
Limited everything. A step above the typical USA lounges, just more food. Not many adult beverage options.
No longer accepts American Express and was full so would not accept Priority Pass.
Very spacious lounge with great breakfast options - cheesy potatoes, congee, sausage cabbage stir fry. Lounge felt clean and updated and showers were also nice.
Massage chairs +100. Champagne selection -50. KFC +20. Showers +30. Overall positive for a business lounge.
Visited during breakfast (7:15). Scrambled eggs, pork sausage, dumplings and potatoes, all warm and fresh. Salad, yoghurt and ramen available.
Nice looking and very comfortable lounge, but extremely weak on food (at least in the morning). A small plate of sandwiches was set out, quickly devoured, and never replaced.
They are declining Priority Pass customers even if you are flying Asiana. They should just remove it from the list of available lounges.
No longer accepting Priority Pass. I even was flying business class and they denied me.
Incredibly crowded. Clearly not limited to Business Class passengers.
Quiet spaces, plenty of food and drink options, rest areas and showers!
Was happily let in when all other PP lounges were crazy full. Small selection of premium liquor. Comfy chairs and nice large TVs.
Arrived mid afternoon Christmas Day with Priority Pass onlyâ€”got in without any fuss, lounge was quiet and relaxing.
Rejected. Donâ€™t bother if you have Priority Pass.

One of my worst lounge experiences.

Overcrowded and with kids running around. No seats available and very few staff were around to clear the tables when vacated.

I would recommend SilverKris.
Dark, library-like atmosphere. Slightly crowded around the buffet and food & beverage quality was sub-par with few spirits and Carlsberg on tap.
Lack of choices over food; crowded. Only slightly better than North American lounges...
There were very limited food options for anyone who isn't into carbs. No yogurt or eggs. My health condition requires avoiding carbs so I was completely out of luck.
The space is very nicely appointed, albeit fake decor, with a classier-than-average clientele. There are no feral children running around and it is very quiet. The one negative is the TERRIBLE food.
Great lounge! Spacious, comfortable, relaxing.  Food is okay, could be better. Good alcohol selection.
Limited food choices on either side, but it does have showers, secluded spaces and even massage chairs!
Very nice lounge but limited hot food and beverage choices. I prefer to go to the Skyhub lounge.
4 stars for the best massage chairs I've seen at lounges to date. 2 stars for food selection compared to the other lounges. As others recommended, eat at the other Sky Lounge and then relax here.
This is pretty small and a bit dated.  There are a few private nooks that fill up that would be good for a nap.
Huge lounge, showers, massage chairs, okay food, lots of outlets, overall classy sexy office/library feel.
Everything is great except the food selection, which is better at the Hub lounge. If you are looking for a meal, go there, otherwise go to Asiana!
Nice lounge with excellent massage chairs, awesome showers and decent food options. Never seemed crowded on the right side of the lounge. Very friendly staff. Large windows allow in natural light.
Crowded lounge, medium level food and filled with giant Korean televisions. Quite noisy as there is no buffer from the general concourse.
A rather mediocre lounge - minimal food choices, no champagne, relaxation/massage rooms always busy (people actually sleeping in massage chairs). Was expecting more from Asiana in its hub airport.
Very nice lounge. Breakfast options were decent (Asian+western options). Great airport views. Renovated side is slightly nicer. Not enough massage chairs, however. Washrooms very nice.
This is a nice lounge, but has poor food options.
Expansive lounge, hot and cold food options, decent liquor choices and fast internet. Plus, great view of planes. I like the right side where the seats are all facing the windows.
There are three shower rooms and they are beyond excellent. Everything is super clean and organized, the staffs are well mannered.
The food is great, and the seats are so comfortable! The service is also wonderful.
This lounge is larger than the one in Concourse A, with more warm food options. Despite the size, it felt a little crowded and overrun, and the massage chairs are always occupied.
Absolutely excellent lounge! All of the offerings and amenities exceeded my expectations.

location.terminalDirections: After Passport Control, the lounge is located on the 4th Floor, near Gate 26.
After Passport Control, located on the 4th Floor, near Gate 11.
East Wing of Terminal 1, take the escalator opposite Gate 11 to the 4th Floor. Follow signs for the 'Transit Hotel' to the lounge entrance.
West Wing of Terminal 1, take the escalator opposite Gate 43 to the 4th Floor.

otherLounges.name: Sky Hub Lounge East (Temporarily Closed For Renovation)

location.terminalDirections: After Passport Control, 4th Floor, next to the Transit Counter, opposite Gate 11.
After Customs, Immigration and Quarantine Area, proceed down the terminal basement and take the 'Starline'. The lounge is located on the 4th Floor of the East Side of Concourse A, near Gate 115.
